In the back seat of the car, Biff turned frequently to look at the unconscious form beside him. To his relief, Captain Royal was still breathing.\par
"I think the old chap will pull through all right," he said to himself.\par
Up a dark, quiet street sped the car, then came to a stop before a massive stone house with a neat gilt plate beside the door. The motorcycles roared up and the boys dismounted.\par
"We'll take him in and let the doctor have a look at him," said Mr. Jacobson. "If he is in bad shape, the doc will put him in his own private hospital. He'll get the best of care here.'*\par
Carefully, they carried Captain Royal up the steps. Their ring was answered by a servant, and they took the old man into a waiting room. The doctor, who had been in bed, soon came downstairs in pyjamas and dressing gown.\par
"An accident case, Doctor," explained Frank. "This old man fell off a cliff into the sea and he's been unconscious for eight or nine hours."\par
194 The Secret of the Caves\par
The doctor made a swift examination. His frown deepened as he inspected the cut on Captain Royal's temple.\par
"Queer!" he said. "It isn't a very bad cut, and there seems to he no sign of a fracture. It looks like concussion of the brain, to me, but he doesn't appear to have had a very hard blow."\par
"The waves washed him up against the rocks," said Joe.\par
The doctor shook his head.\par
"He seems in a bad way. Eight hours, you said?"\par
"Yes."\par
"I'll have to give him a more detailed examination. I'll admit him as a patient to my own hospital if you people will be responsible for him."\par
"That's all right, Doctor. Do what you can for him and send the bill to us," said Frank promptly.\par
The doctor rang a bell. An attendant appeared, wheeling a long, white table. Captain Royal was placed upon it and wheeled away.\par
"I'll let you know in the morning," promised the doctor. "Frankly, I don't mind telling you he's in bad shape. He may never regain consciousness again."\par
The boys were sobered by the thought that Captain Eoyal, for all his eccentricities, might be dying as a result of his wild dash over the\par
Back to Bayport 195\par
rocks. Slowly they filed out into the street, bade good-bye to Mr. Jacobson and thanked him for his assistance, then went home. As Chet Morton lived out in the country, the Hardy boys invited him to spend the rest of the night with them. He accepted the invitation gladly, for the prospect of a long trip out of the city had not appealed to him. Biff Hooper, who lived near by, went to his own home.\par
The house was in darkness when they arrived, so the Hardy boys and Chet quietly parked their motorcycles, slipped up the back stairs and were soon in bed. They were so tired after their adventures of the day that in spite of the temptation to discuss matters, sleep soon overcame them.\par
CHAPTER XXIV at the hospital\par
next morning, refreshed by their sleep, Frank, Joe and Chet were downstairs early, but not earlier than Fenton Hardy, who was already busy in his office clearing up some work before breakfast. He welcomed them cheerily.\par
"Back so soon!" he exclaimed. "I thought this trip would keep you away at least a week,, What's the matter? Did you get frightened by the sea serpent?"\par
"We didn't get frightened, Dad. We had to come back with a man who got hurt."\par
"Oh." Fenton Hardy's expression changed to one of concern. "Who is he?"\par
"We think he's Todham Todd."\par
"Todham Todd!" exclaimed the detective. "Are you sure?"\par
'' We 're not sure. But we have an idea that's who he is. And he may be a murderer too."\par
Mr. Hardy motioned the three boys to chairs. "Sit down and tell me all about it. A murderer ! That sounds bad.''\par
196\par
At the Hospital 197\par
With Frank as spokesman, and Chet and Joe prompting him once in a while, they told Mr. Hardy about their meeting with Captain Royal, about the eccentric behavior of the old ma\'bb and of his actions on finding the brothers look' ing over the clippings in the cave, culminating in his fall from the cliff.\par
"And he's at the private hospital now," concluded Frank.\par
"Well," said Mr. Hardy, "we'll have breakfast now and then we can soon settle the matter once and for all. Evangeline Todd is staying at the summer hotel and we can ask her to come over to the hospital and have a look at this Captain Royal."\par
"Do you think he can be this Lieutenant Pat-wick, Dad?" asked Joe.\par
"Possibly. If so, the crime may have turned his mind. Such things have happened."\par
' 'Well, if he's Patwick then we '11 have cleared up something anyway," remarked Frank.\par
Breakfast was announced a few minutes later, and after the Hardy boys had been warmly greeted by their mother they sat down to fruit, bacon and eggs, toast and coffee and jam, to which they did full justice. They were anxious, however, to call on Miss Todd.\par
Mr. Hardy called up the private hospital and inquired about Captain Royal. He came back, his face serious.\par
198 The Secret of the Caves\par
"The old chap is still unconscious. The doctor seems to think he has only a slim chance."\par
"It will be tough if he turns out to be Tod-ham Todd after all," said Joe. "Too bad if we've found him, only to have him die."\par
"Everything may turn out all right," said Mr. Hardy. "Of course he may not be Tod-ham Todd. You have only your suspicions to go on, although I must say it's very strange that the old man should have had all those lecture clippings in the cave. I've been thinking that Todham Todd may have lost his memory and forgotten his identity. He may have had a dim recollection of once having been a lecturer of some kind so he took to collecting all the newspaper stories he could, in an effort to awaken his memory again."\par
"I'll bet you're right!" exclaimed Chet. 1' That sounds mighty reasonable to me.''\par
"It's just a theory. Still, it may be true. We'll call on Miss Todd."\par
They left the house and went on down to the hotel at which Miss Evangeline Todd was staying. She had just concluded her breakfast when they arrived.\par
"Have you any news?" she asked quickly, when she recognized her visitors.\par
"We have news, of a sort," admitted Fenton Hardy.\par
"Tell me. What is it? Has Todham been\par
At the Hospital 199\par
found? Is he well?" Miss Todd sank back in a chair and fanned herself with a magazine. "Don't keep me in suspense."\par
"We have found a man who may or may not be your brother."\par
"Where is he?" demanded Miss Todd, get-ting up quickly. "Take me to him at once?"\par
Mr. Hardy laid a restraining hand upon her arm.\par
"Don't count on this too much, Miss Todd," he advised. "This man may not be your brother at all. As a matter of fact, we have nothing definite to go on, but we'd like to have you come with us and identify him if you can."\par
'' Identify him ? Is he dead ?"\par
"No. But he's in a local hospital."\par
"Todham in a hospital? Where? I must go to him at once."\par
