of their journey down the long corridor she talked only in whispers. At length they reached the door of a private room. The nurse knocked. The boys heard the doctor's voice, saying, "Come!"\par
The nurse held open the door and they entered a spacious private room, spotlessly clean and well-lighted. Lying on the bed was Captain Royal, with a white bandage around his head.\par
Evangeline Todd looked at the man wildly, then rushed to the bedside.\par
"My brother!" she cried. "It's my brother, Todham!"\par
She leaned over the unconscious figure.\par
"Speak to me, Todham! Speak to me! Don't you recognize me? It's you're sister. I've hunted everywhere for you, and now \i I \i0 've found you at last."\par
Then, overcome with emotion, she sank beside the bed and burst into tears.\par
"It's the missing professor, after all!" exclaimed Chet, in awe.\par
The Hardy boys, while they had expected that Evangeline Todd would identify Captain Royal as her brother, were electrified with delight.\par
"We were right!" said Frank. "He was Todham Todd all along."\par
Mr. Hardy and the doctor tried to calm the\par
202 The Secret of the Caves\par
weeping woman, who was almost hysterical with relief, now that her long search was ended.\par
"It's Todham!" she said, over and over again. "It's my brother. I would know him anywhere."\par
But the man in the bed knew nothing of what was going on. His eyes were closed. His face was white and calm. Had it not been for an occasional slight twitching of the nostrils one might have thought that he was dead.\par
The doctor, who knew nothing of the reason for Miss Todd's outburst, was astonished, but in a few words Fenton Hardy explained the situation to him. He shook his head sadly.\par
"And this is where she has found her brother, at last?"\par
"Yes. He has been missing for months."\par
"I'm afraid," said the doctor, "that she has found him only to lose him."\par
"Is it that serious?"\par
"It's concussion of the brain, and there seem to have been complications. He has only a slim chance to live."\par
CHAPTER XXV\par
the last of captain royal\par
todham todd hovered between life and death for almost two weeks. For days he lay unconscious, knowing nothing of the efforts that were being made to save him. He had the best of care, and the doctor gave him every attention, but admitted that the case was one in which he could do little.\par
"We simply have to wait," he told the Hardy boys and Miss Todd. "He may be restored to consciousness at any moment. On the other hand, he may die just as quickly. He has a good constitution, so we may at least hope for the best."\par
They were anxious days. Every morning, the Hardy boys called at the hospital to inquire about the strange patient, and every morning the answer was the same.\par
"Mr. Todd's condition is unchanged."\par
One morning Fenton Hardy came to his sons with a newspaper in his hand. He was smiling broadly.\par
203\par
204 The Secret of the Caves\par
"I think the mystery is explained," he said. "Bead this."\par
In the newspaper was an account of the capture of Lieutenant Patwick. The man had been shot down on the seacoast by detectives. Thinking he was going to die, he had admitted the murder of Barton Bixby. He also spoke of hiding in a cave with a strange old man, a lunatic.\par
"Todham. Todd," murmured Frank.\par
"That makes everything as clear as day," added Joe.\par
"He must have left his clippings with Captain Royal," said Mr. Hardy. "Murderers usually like to read all that is printed about their crimes."\par
The boys told Evangeline Todd the entire story of their meeting with Captain Eoyal, although in deference to the good lady's feelings they refrained from mentioning the fight in the cave or the incident of the shotgun. How Todham Todd had found his way down to the coast and what had prompted him to call himself Captain Eoyal and take up his hermit existence in the cave, were mysteries.\par
"If he recovers, he may remember nothing about that phase," the doctor had said. "You may use your own judgment whether to tell him of it or not."\par
"We shan't tell him," declared Evangeline\par
The Last of Captain Eoyal 205\par
Todd decisively. "Let him take up the threads of his old life anew."\par
Then her face clouded.\par
"That is-if he recovers," she added, with a catch in her voice.\par
There came a morning when the nurse in charge saw the eyelids of the sick man nutter, and then he spoke.\par
"Where am I?" he asked, in a puzzled tone.\par
"You are quite safe," the nurse told him. "You have met with an accident. You are in the hospital."\par
"Ah, yes," he said. "I remember now. There was a railroad accident. Something must have struck me on the head. I can remember a sudden blow, and that is all."\par
"You have been unconscious for a long time, Captain. You must be quiet."\par
"Captain?" he said. "I'm not a captain. My name is Todd. My name is Todham Todd. I'm a professor at the university."\par
The doctor was called. He questioned the patient carefully and it was soon evident that Todham Todd had recovered his memory with the exception of the time following the first accident that had resulted in amnesia. From that time, everything was a blank. He knew nothing of his wanderings, knew nothing of what had happened in the caves, knew nothing of the accident that had restored his memory again.\par
206 The Secret of the Caves\par
"He will live," the doctor told Evangeline Todd a short time later. "His memory is completely restored. Unless complications set in, he should be able to leave the hospital within a few days."\par
The doctor's prediction was correct.\par
Todham Todd, completely restored in memory, was able to leave the hospital before the week was out. The reunion between the man and his sister was an affectionate one. The professor had not the slightest inkling of all the strange events that had transpired from the time of the first accident until he woke up in the hospital at Bayport. He was deeply puzzled when he learned where he was, but the doctor covered up his bewilderment by explaining that his case had been so unusual that he had been brought there for special treatment when the doctors of his home city had failed to bring him back to consciousness.\par
He was introduced to the Hardy boys by Miss Todd, who was pathetically grateful to the lads for restoring her brother to her, safe and sound again. But there was no sign of recognition. Seeing the boys struck no responsive chord in Professor Todd's memory. He knew nothing of the days when he had played at being Captain Royal. To all intents and purposes, he was seeing the Hardy boys for the first time.\par
The Last of Captain Eoyal 207\par
They were content to let it remain at that and were careful to say nothing that might indicate they had known him previously. And when Todham Todd finally left the hospital and went to the hotel where his sister was staying, to rest there a few days before going back home, the Hardy boys were his firm friends.\par
"We must never let him know," said Evan-geline Todd to the boys that evening.\par
"You may rely on us, Miss Todd," they assured her.\par
"I can't tell you how grateful I am," she said. "If you boys had not been shrewd enough to think that Captain Eoyal might be Todham Todd after all, things might not have turned out as they have. You might not have concerned yourselves with him any more, and he might still be living that wretched life in the caves. I want to reward your father and yourselves for finding him."\par
But Fenton Hardy had already expressed himself on the subject of the reward.\par
"I want nothing," he said. "You have already paid any expenses I incurred in trying to trace Mr. Todd. As for finding him, the credit belongs to the boys."\par
But the Hardy boys were insistent in their refusal.\par
"'We're only too glad that we helped find him," they told Miss Todd. "We couldn't ac-\par
208 The Secret of the Caves\par
cept a reward for what we did. In a way, it was chance that threw him in our path.''\par
Although Miss Todd pleaded with them to alter their decision, they were firm.\par
"Our greatest reward is in seeing your brother with you again, with his memory restored," declared Frank. "'We want nothing more than that."\par
But Miss Todd expressed her appreciation in tangible form before she left Bayport. She invited the Hardy boys and some of their chums, Chet Morton, Biff Hooper, Phil Cohen, Tony Prito, Jack Dodd and Jerry Gilroy, to a banquet at the hotel, and there the lads sat down to a "spread" the like of which they had not seen before. There was everything dear to the heart of a boy, from fried chicken, fluffy mashed potatoes and sweet pickels, to icecream and five different kinds of pie.\par
Professor Todham Todd, white-haired, kindly-faced, looking quite different from the wild-eyed Captain Eoyal of Honeycomb Caves, presided at the banquet and made a little speech in which he thanked them all for their interest in his welfare and their kindness to him. Although he had no idea of the real part the Hardy boys and their chums had played in his recovery, he had taken a genuine liking to them and it is probable that he enjoyed the banquet as much as any one.\par
The Last of Captain Royal 209\par
When the lads had eaten of chicken and icecream until they could eat no more, Miss Todd stood up and said she had an announcement to make.\par
"You all know something of the circumstances under which we have gathered here tonight. You all know the debt of gratitude I owe to the Hardy boys, in particular, and to Chet Morton and Biff Hooper. So if they will stand up, I have something for them."\par
Blushing, the four lads got to their feet.\par
"All I can say," continued Miss Todd, "is that my brother and I thank you very, very much."\par
